   <h1>Re: [VB] Whats this wire? (BN4 Heater)</h1>
   <b>Sean Dorman &lt;croftyest_at_yahoo_dot_com&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2001-12-28 20:05:54+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>Ark Mirvis in NJ has diaphrams. (Look in links on
vintagebus_dot_com or on VW Planet). I think he was asking
$55.00 for them so i was going to try to fab my own
using directions from type2_dot_com.
More than likely you diaphram is shot but try pulling
apart the fuel pump and cleaninig it out. they tend to
freeze up if not used for a while. It worked with the
ones i have!

Sean 
65 Westfalia
67 Nissan Patrol

--- Claralw_at_aol_dot_com wrote:
> Talking about BN-4s, I was thinking I should get one
> going and put it in a 
> bus while I have some time.    Mine the fuel pump is
> dead (surprise).  What 
> was that sources for buying modern fuel pumps for
> the eberspacher?  Was it 
> from espar, the modern incarnation of eberspacher?
> 
> definately before installing the heater (if it is
> out) test it on a bench.   
> I did this hooking ground to ground and positive to
> positive.  Two wires have 
> to have electricity to start the heater.  one is
> always on, one you turn it 
> on .   Then what happened is my blower motor blew,
> but it did not sucks gas 
> out of the gas can.   er, I would have to look at
> the heater again to be more 
> specific on which wire is what.   there is the
> wiring diagram on the web at 
> one of those obsolete VW document sites
> 
>
http://www.conservatory_dot_com/vw/manuals_nyx/EberBN4.html
> 
> 
> In a message dated 12/28/01 6:41:39 AM Pacific
> Standard Time, 
> jbakerccymca_at_springmail_dot_com writes:
> 
> << 
>  OK folks,
>  Got a Bn4 and I dont know what one wire is.  Coming
> off of the fuel pump 
> there is a red wire that goes to a bolt on the
> bracket, at this braket the 
> wire has a "y" and becomes 2 wires, one wire goesi
> nto the body of the 
> heater, the other eone is hanging loos with no
> connectoer on the end.  WHERE 
> DOES THIS WIRE GO???  Anticipating heat, John Baker
>   >>
> 
